Execution ¬∂

The execution subpackage groups components relating to the execution stack for the platform.

The layered architecture of the execution stack somewhat mirrors the data stack with a central engine, cache layer beneath, database layer beneath, with alternative implementations able to be written on top.

Due to the high-performance, the core components are reusable between both backtest and live implementations - helping to ensure consistent logic for trading operations.

Components ¬∂

class ExecAlgorithm ( config : Optional [ ExecAlgorithmConfig ] = None ) ¬∂

Bases: Actor

The base class for all execution algorithms.

This class allows traders to implement their own customized execution algorithms.

Parameters :

config ( ExecAlgorithmConfig , optional ) ‚Äì The execution algorithm configuration.

Raises :

TypeError ‚Äì If config is not of type ExecAlgorithmConfig .

Warning

This class should not be used directly, but through a concrete subclass.

add_synthetic ( self , SyntheticInstrument synthetic ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Add the created synthetic instrument to the cache.

Parameters :

synthetic ( SyntheticInstrument ) ‚Äì The synthetic instrument to add to the cache.

Raises :

KeyError ‚Äì If synthetic is already in the cache.

Notes

If you are updating the synthetic instrument then you should use the update_synthetic method.

cache ¬∂

The read-only cache for the actor.

Returns :

CacheFacade

cancel_order ( self , Order order , ClientId client_id=None ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Cancel the given order with optional routing instructions.

A CancelOrder command will be created and then sent to either the OrderEmulator or the RiskEngine (depending on whether the order is emulated).

Logs an error if no VenueOrderId has been assigned to the order.

Parameters :

  • order ( Order ) ‚Äì The order to cancel.

  • client_id ( ClientId , optional ) ‚Äì The specific client ID for the command. If None then will be inferred from the venue in the instrument ID.

clock ¬∂

The actors clock.

Returns :

Clock

config ¬∂

The actors configuration.

Returns :

NautilusConfig

degrade ( self ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Degrade the component.

While executing on_degrade() any exception will be logged and reraised, then the component will remain in a DEGRADING state.

Warning

Do not override.

If the component is not in a valid state from which to execute this method, then the component state will not change, and an error will be logged.

deregister_warning_event ( self , type event ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Deregister the given event type from warning log levels.

Parameters :

event ( type ) ‚Äì The event class to deregister.

dispose ( self ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Dispose of the component.

While executing on_dispose() any exception will be logged and reraised, then the component will remain in a DISPOSING state.

Warning

Do not override.

If the component is not in a valid state from which to execute this method, then the component state will not change, and an error will be logged.

execute ( self , TradingCommand command ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Handle the given trading command by processing it with the execution algorithm.

Parameters :

command ( SubmitOrder ) ‚Äì The command to handle.

Raises :

ValueError ‚Äì If command.exec_algorithm_id is not equal to self.id

fault ( self ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Fault the component.

Calling this method multiple times has the same effect as calling it once (it is idempotent). Once called, it cannot be reversed, and no other methods should be called on this instance.

While executing on_fault() any exception will be logged and reraised, then the component will remain in a FAULTING state.

Warning

Do not override.

If the component is not in a valid state from which to execute this method, then the component state will not change, and an error will be logged.

classmethod fully_qualified_name ( cls ) ‚Üí str ¬∂

Return the fully qualified name for the components class.

Returns :

str

modify_order ( self , Order order , Quantity quantity=None , Price price=None , Price trigger_price=None , ClientId client_id=None ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Modify the given order with optional parameters and routing instructions.

An ModifyOrder command will be created and then sent to the RiskEngine .

At least one value must differ from the original order for the command to be valid.

Will use an Order Cancel/Replace Request (a.k.a Order Modification) for FIX protocols, otherwise if order update is not available for the API, then will cancel and replace with a new order using the original ClientOrderId .

Parameters :

  • order ( Order ) ‚Äì The order to update.

  • quantity ( Quantity , optional ) ‚Äì The updated quantity for the given order.

  • price ( Price , optional ) ‚Äì The updated price for the given order (if applicable).

  • trigger_price ( Price , optional ) ‚Äì The updated trigger price for the given order (if applicable).

  • client_id ( ClientId , optional ) ‚Äì The specific client ID for the command. If None then will be inferred from the venue in the instrument ID.

Raises :

  • ValueError ‚Äì If price is not None and order does not have a price .

  • ValueError ‚Äì If trigger is not None and order does not have a trigger_price .

Warning

If the order is already closed or at PENDING_CANCEL status then the command will not be generated, and a warning will be logged.

References

https://www.onixs.biz/fix-dictionary/5.0.SP2/msgType_G_71.html

submit_order ( self , Order order ) ‚Üí void ¬∂

Submit the given order (may be the primary or spawned order).

A SubmitOrder command will be created and sent to the RiskEngine .

If the client order ID is duplicate, then the order will be denied.

Parameters :

  • order ( Order ) ‚Äì The order to submit.

  • parent_order_id ( ClientOrderId , optional ) ‚Äì The parent client order identifier. If provided then will be considered a child order of the parent.

Raises :

  • ValueError ‚Äì If order.status is not INITIALIZED .

  • ValueError ‚Äì If order.emulation_trigger is not None .

Warning

If a position_id is passed and a position does not yet exist, then any position opened by the order will have this position ID assigned. This may not be what you intended.

Emulated orders cannot be sent from execution algorithms (intentioally constraining complexity).

Subscribe to OrderBook snapshots at a specified interval, for the given instrument ID.

The DataEngine will only maintain one order book for each instrument. Because of this - the level, depth and kwargs for the stream will be set as per the last subscription request (this will also affect all subscribers).

Parameters :

  • instrument_id ( InstrumentId ) ‚Äì The order book instrument ID to subscribe to.

  • book_type (BookType { L1_TBBO , L2_MBP , L3_MBO }) ‚Äì The order book type.

  • depth ( int , optional ) ‚Äì The maximum depth for the order book. A depth of 0 is maximum depth.

  • interval_ms ( int ) ‚Äì The order book snapshot interval in milliseconds.

  • kwargs ( dict , optional ) ‚Äì The keyword arguments for exchange specific parameters.

  • client_id ( ClientId , optional ) ‚Äì The specific client ID for the command. If None then will be inferred from the venue in the instrument ID.

Raises :

  • ValueError ‚Äì If depth is negative (< 0).

  • ValueError ‚Äì If interval_ms is not positive (> 0).

The ExecutionEngine is the central component of the entire execution stack.

The execution engines primary responsibility is to orchestrate interactions between the ExecutionClient instances, and the rest of the platform. This includes sending commands to, and receiving events from, the trading venue endpoints via its registered execution clients.

The engine employs a simple fan-in fan-out messaging pattern to execute TradingCommand messages, and process AccountState or OrderEvent type messages.

Alternative implementations can be written on top of the generic engine - which just need to override the execute and process methods.
